      <header class="post-header">

        
        
          <h1 class="post-title" itemprop="name headline">Why deep?</h1>
        

        <div class="post-meta">
          <span class="post-time">
            
              <span class="post-meta-item-icon">
                <i class="fa fa-calendar-o"></i>
              </span>
              
                <span class="post-meta-item-text">Posted on</span>
              
              <time title="Post created" itemprop="dateCreated datePublished" datetime="2017-09-24T19:41:26+10:00">
                2017-09-24
              </time>
            

            

            
          </span>

          
            <span class="post-category" >
            
              <span class="post-meta-divider">|</span>
            
              <span class="post-meta-item-icon">
                <i class="fa fa-folder-o"></i>
              </span>
              
                <span class="post-meta-item-text">In</span>
              
              
                <span itemprop="about" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Thing">
                  <a href="/categories/Intuition/" itemprop="url" rel="index">
                    <span itemprop="name">Intuition</span>
                  </a>
                </span>

                
                
              
            </span>
          

          
            
          

          
          

          

          

          

        </div>
      </header>
    

    
    
    
    <div class="post-body" itemprop="articleBody">

      
      

      
        <p>The key idea about why deep network works better is: <strong>Modularization</strong>.</p>
<p>We treat each neuron in the first layer as most basic classifier. Then the second layer use first layer as module to build classifiers, and so on. The modularization is automatically learned from data. The benefit is that we simplified our learning task, we need less training data to train our deep models.</p>
<p><strong>Universality Theorem</strong>: Any continuous function f <span class="math display">\[f: R^N \rightarrow R^M\]</span> Can be realized by a network with one hidden layer.</p>
<p>Yes, shallow network can represent any function given <strong>enough hidden neurons</strong>. However, using deep structure is more effective.</p>
<p>For complex task, very similar inputs have different outputs but very different inputs have similar output.</p>
<p>To learn moreâ€¦ <a href="http://research.microsoft.com/apps/video/default.aspx?id=%20232373&amp;r=1" target="_blank" rel="external">Do deep nets really need to be deep? (by Rich Caruana)</a></p>

      
    </div>
    
    
    

    

    

    

